at Google and around the world

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:39.200
are going to be inspired to
contribute to what is already

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:40.290
a very large project.

00:01:40.290 --> 00:01:42.000
But the bottom line
is that this project

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.560
went open source
a few months ago

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:48.710
and is hopefully going to become
a very big worldwide effort

00:01:48.710 --> 00:01:53.680
that will let the public share
in the joy that is astronomy.

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:57.780
So let me tell you very quickly
how I wound up standing here

00:01:57.780 --> 00:02:01.490
and what WorldWide
Telescope has meant to me.

00:02:01.490 --> 00:02:04.360
So the first picture
that you see here

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:08.250
on the left, this picture is
my friend and colleague Curtis

00:02:08.250 --> 00:02:09.039
Wong.

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:10.840
And then this picture is me.

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:14.360
And we were at a meeting, the
first astronomy visualization

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:17.430
meaning that either Curtis
or I had ever gone to,

00:02:17.430 --> 00:02:20.040
in Chicago in 2005.

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:22.745
And we were both sent
there by friends.

00:02:22.745 --> 00:02:25.390
It was almost like being
fixed up on a blind date.

00:02:25.390 --> 00:02:27.220
So we were sent
there by friends who

00:02:27.220 --> 00:02:30.460
thought that we would both
enjoy a little respite

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:32.000
from our normal
meeting schedule.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.250
And let's go this fun astronomy
visualization meeting.

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:36.249
Because I have interest
in both of those things,

00:02:36.249 --> 00:02:38.980
but never in
specifically outreach

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:41.760
and that kind of
visualization in astronomy.

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:44.940
And Curtis Wong had
done a lot of work

00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:48.570
using cutting edge
media to tell stories

00:02:48.570 --> 00:02:50.320
about interesting subjects.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:55.380
So he made an incredible
CD-ROM about Leonardo da Vinci

00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:57.344
that some of you may have seen.

00:02:57.344 --> 00:02:59.010
Another one about the
Barnes Foundation.

00:02:59.010 --> 00:03:02.930
But anyway, he's all about
integrating audio, and video,

00:03:02.930 --> 00:03:05.880
and data, and text, and
all kinds of information

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:08.580
in as seamless an environment
as you can possibly

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:11.700
offer for somebody to explore
and learn on their own.

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:13.740
So at this meeting,
I was talking

00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:15.800
about a new project
we had started where

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:18.320
we were using medical
imaging software

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:21.691
on high dimensional
astronomy data.

00:03:21.691 --> 00:03:24.190
And that's not something I'm
going to talk much about today.

00:03:24.190 --> 00:03:26.140
Ask me afterwards if you
want to know more about it.

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:27.210
We're still doing it.

00:03:27.210 --> 00:03:30.480
We have a new software
effort on that separate

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:32.120
from WorldWide
Telescope called GLUE.

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:34.910
That's a high dimensional
data visualization program.

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:38.130
But Curtis was talking
about this dream

00:03:38.130 --> 00:03:41.890
that he had to take all this
astronomy data that was online

00:03:41.890 --> 00:03:43.910
and make it available
to people as kind

00:03:43.910 --> 00:03:48.450
of a substrate for a program
that would let you move

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:50.170
through the sky or
through the universe

00:03:50.170 --> 00:03:53.110
and tell stories about
astronomy and about the universe

00:03:53.110 --> 00:03:54.160
to each other.

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:56.070
And the idea was
that you would build

00:03:56.070 --> 00:04:00.360
these tours of the universe
where an object in the sky

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:02.720
would be almost like a
weird little celestial

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:05.384
hyperlink, where you
could be at that object

00:04:05.384 --> 00:04:06.800
and you could be
there because you

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:08.258
were trying to
learn about nebulae,

00:04:08.258 --> 00:04:10.216
but somehow, something
about that object

00:04:10.216 --> 00:04:11.590
would reveal that,
actually, it's

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:14.102
also in the catalogue of
somebody named Messier

00:04:14.102 --> 00:04:15.560
and that this is
somehow important.

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:17.732
And you could learn about
the Messier catalogue.

00:04:17.732 --> 00:04:19.940
When I show you the software
the now actually exists,

00:04:19.940 --> 00:04:22.231
you'll see a little bit more
of what I'm talking about.

00:04:22.231 --> 00:04:26.000
But basically, Curtis
described this dream

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:29.130
that he had that
wasn't yet a reality.

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.550
And I told him that
that sounded great

00:04:31.550 --> 00:04:35.130
and that I would basically
help him if he ever did that.

00:04:35.130 --> 00:04:38.240
And so, in the end, he did
get a chance to do that.

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:40.310
I'll tell you more
about that later.

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:42.170
And the software
was coded mostly

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:45.640
by one unbelievable
software architect

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:48.684
named Jonathan Fay, who I will
tell you more about later.

00:04:48.684 --> 00:04:50.600
You're not going to
believe-- maybe you will--

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:53.000
but that this was made
mostly by one person.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.880
Anyway, so in 2005,
this was just a dream.

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:59.450
By 2008-- and the
meeting was in Chicago.

00:04:59.450 --> 00:05:01.430
And then a young
six-year-old in Chicago

00:05:01.430 --> 00:05:04.102
used the software to make
a tour, which I'll show you

00:05:04.102 --> 00:05:06.560
in a minute, one of these tours
inside WorldWide Telescope.

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:10.220
Tell us about what
he sees in Chicago.

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:13.290
And then by about
2010, the software

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:16.190
was so capable that it was
used by the Adler Planetarium

00:05:16.190 --> 00:05:21.280
in Chicago to make a
completely digital planetarium

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:24.640
show for what turned out to
be about 1/10 the cost of what

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:28.750
a planetarium show
normally costs to produce.

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:32.691
And then, about a year
ago, it became clear

00:05:32.691 --> 00:05:35.190
that it was going to be possible
to make WorldWide Telescope

00:05:35.190 --> 00:05:35.970
open source.

00:05:35.970 --> 00:05:37.990
I'll tell you more
about the details later.

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:40.045
But it had been seven
years since it started.

00:05:40.045 --> 00:05:41.870
And Microsoft had spent
about $10 million.

00:05:41.870 --> 00:05:45.240
I forgot to mention that Curtis
Wong and Jonathan Fay worked

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:46.910
at Microsoft Research.

00:05:46.910 --> 00:05:49.810
And so this project,
which is now open source,

00:05:49.810 --> 00:05:51.160
did start at Microsoft Research.

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:55.300
So yes, I feel honored
to be coming to Google

00:05:55.300 --> 00:05:57.100
and telling you
about a project that

00:05:57.100 --> 00:05:59.880
started at Microsoft Research
that you can participate in

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.310
if you'd like.

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:03.620
Anyway, so we had this meeting.

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:06.312
There's a series of meetings
in astronomy called .Astronomy,

00:06:06.312 --> 00:06:08.270
which is for people who
are interested in using

00:06:08.270 --> 00:06:13.030
the internet to both do
astronomy research and outreach

00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:14.820
and also education.

00:06:14.820 --> 00:06:17.190
And so at the annual
meeting last year,

00:06:17.190 --> 00:06:20.349
which was oddly enough at the
Adler Planetarium in Chicago,

00:06:20.349 --> 00:06:21.890
we made a video that
you can go watch

00:06:21.890 --> 00:06:23.556
about how much everybody
loves WorldWide

00:06:23.556 --> 00:06:25.780
Telescope to introduce
it to the world

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:28.730
as a project that was
about to go open source.

