And I do mean the universe.

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:57.103
You can go all the
way out to the edge

00:11:57.103 --> 00:11:59.960
of the observable
universe back in time.

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:01.600
You can look at the Earth.

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:04.090
You can add data to
the Earth or the sky.

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:06.800
You saw before we started
that you can navigate around

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:09.000
on the surface of Mars.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.060
And you can, importantly,
switch back and forth

00:12:12.060 --> 00:12:13.580
between the
three-dimensional views

00:12:13.580 --> 00:12:16.480
and two-dimensional views of
the universe to let people

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:20.620
know what various phenomena
look like on the sky.

00:12:20.620 --> 00:12:23.290
So officially, the
title of this talk

00:12:23.290 --> 00:12:26.320
is Open Source on
a Universal Scale.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:28.380
And the idea is
that this program

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:32.580
has been downloaded as an
application something like 15

00:12:32.580 --> 00:12:33.760
to 20 million times.

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:35.580
We lost count at one point.

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:39.110
And the number of online
users in just a web browser

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:41.290
is also extremely
difficult to count.

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:45.390
But it's in the many tens if not
hundreds of millions of uses.

00:12:45.390 --> 00:12:47.660
So a lot of people
are using this

00:12:47.660 --> 00:12:51.140
for a lot of different
purposes, but we still

00:12:51.140 --> 00:12:53.820
think that much
more could be done.

00:12:53.820 --> 00:12:57.620
So let me explain some
context by going back

00:12:57.620 --> 00:12:59.610
to the history of
astronomy and tell you

00:12:59.610 --> 00:13:02.740
where these kind of
virtual skies came from.

00:13:02.740 --> 00:13:04.940
So if you think
about Stonehenge,

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:07.740
OK, that's where we get
the 3,500 years ago.

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:09.930
That was clearly
one of the earliest

00:13:09.930 --> 00:13:11.730
astronomy observatories.

00:13:11.730 --> 00:13:12.600
No telescopes.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:15.570
And then this picture of
Ptolemy in Alexandria--

00:13:15.570 --> 00:13:16.850
looks like he has a telescope.

00:13:16.850 --> 00:13:19.110
But we should all remember
that Ptolemy was just

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:20.770
looking through a
tube and mapping out

00:13:20.770 --> 00:13:23.530
the positions of stars and
that people started coming up

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:26.110
with theories for how
the heavens worked

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:26.970
at about that time.

00:13:26.970 --> 00:13:28.761
Ptolemy was the one
with all the epicycles,

00:13:28.761 --> 00:13:31.740
for those of you who
know what that is.

00:13:31.740 --> 00:13:35.010
And then people built fancier
and fancier facilities

00:13:35.010 --> 00:13:36.960
for observing the heavens.

00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:41.210
But still no telescopes until
Galileo came along a little

00:13:41.210 --> 00:13:44.190
over 400 years ago
at point a telescope,

00:13:44.190 --> 00:13:47.230
which was then a new
gizmo, at the sky.

00:13:47.230 --> 00:13:48.872
And he learned a lot of things.

00:13:48.872 --> 00:13:50.830
You saw, at the beginning,
I was playing around

00:13:50.830 --> 00:13:52.610
with the WorldWide
Telescope tour that

00:13:52.610 --> 00:13:55.780
explains how important
Galileo's discovery of the moons

00:13:55.780 --> 00:13:58.360
of Jupiter was to our
understanding of the Earth's

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:00.960
place and the Sun's place
in the solar system.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:05.730
So again, then something
tremendously important

00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:08.030
happened right around
the time of Galileo.

00:14:08.030 --> 00:14:12.720
You have this shift in science
to a data-driven approach

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:15.190
where your theories have
to be actually verified

00:14:15.190 --> 00:14:16.550
by observations.

00:14:16.550 --> 00:14:19.730
And astronomy was a big
part of that transition.

00:14:19.730 --> 00:14:23.000
And so if we skip way ahead
to the 1930s, the reason

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:24.820
that there's a picture
of a radio telescope

00:14:24.820 --> 00:14:27.820
there is because that
was when people stopped

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:29.530
using optical wavelengths.

00:14:29.530 --> 00:14:32.440
So the wavelengths we can see
with our eyes, how many people

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.620
think about astronomy, are
called optical wavelengths.

00:14:35.620 --> 00:14:38.740
And so the first
foray out of that

00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:42.310
was with radio
astronomy in the 1930s.

00:14:42.310 --> 00:14:44.940
And a lot of that technology
was developed hand-in-hand

00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:45.520
with radar.

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:46.831
That's where that came from.

00:14:46.831 --> 00:14:47.330
OK.

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:51.391
So then, the next big milestone
was to leave the Earth.

00:14:51.391 --> 00:14:51.890
OK.

00:14:51.890 --> 00:14:55.620
So the first
space-based observatory

00:14:55.620 --> 00:14:57.680
was NASA's Explorer 7.

00:14:57.680 --> 00:14:59.950
So that was now 1959.

00:14:59.950 --> 00:15:03.030
And then, something that is
most important here at Google,

00:15:03.030 --> 00:15:04.780
comes the advent
of the internet.

00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:07.990
And what's really interesting
to me is that the first thing

00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:10.780
people thought about when they
thought about the internet

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:13.130
and astronomy was, wow, we
don't have go on observing

00:15:13.130 --> 00:15:14.760
and stay up all night anymore.

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:17.170
We're going to build
these robotic telescopes,

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:20.680
and we don't have to
actually go there.

00:15:20.680 --> 00:15:24.910
We can just have instruments
take data for us, which,

00:15:24.910 --> 00:15:27.710
while a good idea and
important in astronomy today,

00:15:27.710 --> 00:15:30.120
is not actually
the real potential

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:31.560
of the internet for astronomy.

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:33.850
The real potential
is in data sharing.

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:34.350
OK.

00:15:34.350 --> 00:15:40.230
And in doing research using
vast, vast repositories now

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.210
of online data.

00:15:42.210 --> 00:15:45.980
And someone asked a question
over the internet about-- I

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:47.480
think in the abstract
for this talk,

00:15:47.480 --> 00:15:50.920
I mentioned that astronomy data
were economically valueless.

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:53.680
And that's why--
yes-- and that's

00:15:53.680 --> 00:15:55.890
why a lot of computer
scientists love

00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:58.080
to work with astronomers
because there's not

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:01.920
a lot of economic
politics that go along

00:16:01.920 --> 00:16:03.910
with sharing data in astronomy.

00:16:03.910 --> 00:16:06.420
And the person asking
the question online

00:16:06.420 --> 00:16:09.013
did point out that,
yes, astronomy data

00:16:09.013 --> 00:16:11.070
have been very important
in navigation and things

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:11.570
like that.

00:16:11.570 --> 00:16:14.690
So indirectly, astronomy
has some economic value.

00:16:14.690 --> 00:16:16.630
But most astronomy
data can be thought

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:23.050
of as valueless in an economic
way and very easy to share.

00:16:23.050 --> 00:16:24.480
So anyway, that's
way astronomers

00:16:24.480 --> 00:16:28.007
are often thought of as in
the forefront of data sharing.

00:16:28.007 --> 00:16:30.590
I'll tell you a little bit more
about the politics of what all

00:16:30.590 --> 00:16:32.377
those logos mean down there.

00:16:32.377 --> 00:16:34.710
But let me just say that I
think that this dividing line

00:16:34.710 --> 00:16:38.500
between pre-telescopic
and telescopic observing

00:16:38.500 --> 00:16:41.050
is as important
as the opportunity

00:16:41.050 --> 00:16:44.111
that we have now, where there's
all of this astronomy data

00:16:44.111 --> 00:16:44.610
online.

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:47.030
And I think the way
that astronomy is done

00:16:47.030 --> 00:16:48.407
has just completely changed.

00:16:48.407 --> 00:16:50.240
And just for fun, I
thought I would give you

00:16:50.240 --> 00:16:52.930
some idea of the financial
numbers involved.

00:16:52.930 --> 00:16:56.870
So just before Galileo
and his telescope,

00:16:56.870 --> 00:17:00.300
Tycho Brahe built two
observatories with money

00:17:00.300 --> 00:17:01.970
from the King of Denmark.

00:17:01.970 --> 00:17:04.050
And the cost of one
of these observatories

00:17:04.050 --> 00:17:08.240
was said to be 1% of the gross
domestic product of Denmark.

00:17:08.240 --> 00:17:08.950
OK.

00:17:08.950 --> 00:17:11.040
And then, by the way, it was
kind of too windy at that one,

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:12.539
so they had to build
the second one.

00:17:12.539 --> 00:17:15.660
And nobody talks about
how much that costs.

00:17:15.660 --> 00:17:18.040
But anyway, so
then-- what is that?

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:21.310
That's 29 years later, Galileo
comes along and disrupts

00:17:21.310 --> 00:17:23.640
this system and starts
using a telescope.

00:17:23.640 --> 00:17:24.140
OK.

00:17:24.140 --> 00:17:27.420
So now, how much did the
Keck Observatory cost?

00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:29.480
So this is a big,
modern telescope,

00:17:29.480 --> 00:17:31.720
the first of its kind in
terms of being really big,

00:17:31.720 --> 00:17:34.890
expensive, 8-meter
class telescopes.

00:17:34.890 --> 00:17:39.891
And that's I think the 0.00002%
of the GDP of the United

00:17:39.891 --> 00:17:40.390
States.

00:17:40.390 --> 00:17:43.790
And this is still considered
an extremely expensive project.

00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:47.130
Well, all the modern things
are even more expensive.

00:17:47.130 --> 00:17:52.570
Anyway, but just for reference,
if you add 29 years to that,

00:17:52.570 --> 00:17:55.360
you would get 2024.

00:17:55.360 --> 00:17:58.110
And I think that it will
be possible to essentially

00:17:58.110 --> 00:18:00.960
have full sky virtual
astronomy at every wavelength

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:03.690
that we know about
by about 2024.

00:18:03.690 --> 00:18:04.680
We almost have it now.

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:05.180
OK.

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:07.170
So the very best
data, the newest data,

00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:09.620
data taken for special
purposes, they're not usually

00:18:09.620 --> 00:18:10.570
immediately shared.

00:18:10.570 --> 00:18:12.827
But almost everything
else actually is.

00:18:12.827 --> 00:18:14.910
And so you should know,
if you don't already know,

00:18:14.910 --> 00:18:17.730
that Google is actually
involved in this big project

00:18:17.730 --> 00:18:21.020
called the LSST, the Large
Synoptic Survey Telescope,

00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:24.240
that surveys the whole sky
essentially every three nights,

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:25.980
and can look for
time varying sources.

00:18:25.980 --> 00:18:31.410
And all of this data is
just an absolute gold mine

00:18:31.410 --> 00:18:35.300
for basically data mining
and trying to understand how

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:37.080
the universe changes with time.

00:18:37.080 --> 00:18:39.530
But most astronomers
are not very well

00:18:39.530 --> 00:18:43.340
equipped to deal with that
kind of big data science.

00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:46.040
So there's a big
effort in astronomy

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:48.270
to try to bring the
techniques of data science

00:18:48.270 --> 00:18:51.710
and visualization more
into the mainstream of how

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:52.500
people do science.

00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:55.192
And WorldWide Telescope is a
little bit of a part of that.

00:18:55.192 --> 00:18:56.900
What I won't talk
about very much today--

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:59.560
but if you're interested
in that aspect of changing

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:01.770
the culture and all these
other tools for data

00:19:01.770 --> 00:19:04.170
sharing and data
visualization, go check out

00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:07.340
our larger group effort, which
is called Seamless Astronomy.

00:19:07.340 --> 00:19:10.940
And it has to do with bringing
data and literature together

00:19:10.940 --> 00:19:12.920
into the hands of a
researcher without them

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:15.452
having to worry exactly
about where it came from.

00:19:15.452 --> 00:19:17.160
But today, I'm going
to talk about what's

00:19:17.160 --> 00:19:19.730
just in this little
shaky blue square, which

00:19:19.730 --> 00:19:22.850
is these tools for
getting to the data

00:19:22.850 --> 00:19:25.920
and looking at it in
the context of the sky.

00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:28.170
So the name,
WorldWide Telescope,

00:19:28.170 --> 00:19:31.060
comes from an article that was
written by Alec Szaley and Jim

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:33.422
Gray in 2001.

00:19:33.422 --> 00:19:35.130
And I'll just read
the introduction here.

00:19:35.130 --> 00:19:37.380
It says, "All astronomy
data and literature

00:19:37.380 --> 00:19:40.460
will soon be online and
accessible via the internet.

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:42.870
The community is building
the Virtual Observatory,

00:19:42.870 --> 00:19:44.870
an organization of
this worldwide data

00:19:44.870 --> 00:19:47.910
into a coherent whole that
can be accessed by anyone

00:19:47.910 --> 00:19:49.940
in any form from anywhere.

00:19:49.940 --> 00:19:51.780
The resulting system
will dramatically

00:19:51.780 --> 00:19:54.740
improve our ability to do
multi-spectral and temporal

00:19:54.740 --> 00:19:57.810
studies that integrate data
from multiple instruments.

00:19:57.810 --> 00:19:59.930
The Virtual
Observatory data also

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:01.940
provide a wonderful base
for teaching astronomy,

00:20:01.940 --> 00:20:04.780
scientific discovery, and
computational science."

00:20:04.780 --> 00:20:10.280
So there's the abstract of
my talk, but written in 2001.

00:20:10.280 --> 00:20:12.350
Now, what's important
is-- how many people here

00:20:12.350 --> 00:20:14.840
know what the Virtual
Observatory is,

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:15.980
what that means?

00:20:15.980 --> 00:20:16.480
Yeah.

00:20:16.480 --> 00:20:20.020
Just a few of the kind of
professional astronomer types.

00:20:20.020 --> 00:20:22.530
And so there's a whole
political back story

00:20:22.530 --> 00:20:27.220
that I'm not going to go into
except for the importance of it

00:20:27.220 --> 00:20:29.650
toward data sharing
and the future.

00:20:29.650 --> 00:20:33.130
And so the extremely short
summary of this story

00:20:33.130 --> 00:20:36.730
is that in 2001, not only
was that article written,

00:20:36.730 --> 00:20:38.420
but the Virtual
Observatory that they're

00:20:38.420 --> 00:20:41.880
talking about in the article
was a government-sponsored NSF

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:44.230
program to try to build
the infrastructure

00:20:44.230 --> 00:20:47.040
to make this vision possible.

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:48.430
And the reason
Jim Gray's picture

00:20:48.430 --> 00:20:50.570
is on there is because
he's one of the co-authors

00:20:50.570 --> 00:20:52.367
of this original article.

00:20:52.367 --> 00:20:54.700
And he's one of the inspirations
for WorldWide Telescope

00:20:54.700 --> 00:20:56.340
that I'll explain in a second.

00:20:56.340 --> 00:20:56.840
OK.

00:20:56.840 --> 00:21:01.540
So in 2002, many countries we're
trying to have these Virtual

00:21:01.540 --> 00:21:02.600
Observatory efforts.

00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:06.110
And so they joined together to
make a standards body basically

00:21:06.110 --> 00:21:08.620
called the IVOA or the
International Virtual

00:21:08.620 --> 00:21:10.600
Observatory Alliance.

00:21:10.600 --> 00:21:15.070
And then in 2007,
two projects started.

00:21:15.070 --> 00:21:16.899
One was called Google Sky.

00:21:16.899 --> 00:21:18.940
And the other one was
called WorldWide Telescope.

00:21:18.940 --> 00:21:23.050
So raise your hand if
you've used Google Sky.

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:24.800
Almost, but not
quite, everybody.

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:27.940
Raise your hand if you
worked on Google Sky.

00:21:27.940 --> 00:21:28.540
No one.

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:29.040
OK.

00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:32.520
So Google Sky is not
officially supported by Google

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:34.500
anymore as far as I know.

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:37.610
And I don't really want to
say this, but I have to.

00:21:37.610 --> 00:21:40.410
So at one of these
meetings in Chicago,

00:21:40.410 --> 00:21:42.640
the team from
Google Sky was there

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:45.010
and the team from WorldWide
Telescope was there.

00:21:45.010 --> 00:21:50.260
And they basically-- Google
Sky conceded defeat by-- yes,

00:21:50.260 --> 00:21:53.640
some Googlers are nodding for
those of you can't see them.

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:56.740
But anyway, by saying,
you guys built a Harley

00:21:56.740 --> 00:21:58.460
and we built a chop shop.

00:21:58.460 --> 00:22:00.245
So go have fun with your Harley.

00:22:00.245 --> 00:22:02.870
And actually, what I'm going to
tell you at the end of the talk

00:22:02.870 --> 00:22:05.790
today is that I think we should
turn a Harley into a chop shop

00:22:05.790 --> 00:22:06.950
a little bit more.

00:22:06.950 --> 00:22:08.810
So you'll see what happens.

00:22:08.810 --> 00:22:11.630
But anyway, in 2007,
some of you may

00:22:11.630 --> 00:22:14.890
remember Jim Gray was a
great database pioneer.

00:22:14.890 --> 00:22:16.261
And he disappeared at sea.

00:22:16.261 --> 00:22:18.260
And there was this worldwide
effort to find him.

00:22:18.260 --> 00:22:19.800
And he was never found.

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:22.710
But as a tribute to
Jim Gray, Bill Gates

00:22:22.710 --> 00:22:25.300
gave Curtis Wong
and Jonathan Fay

00:22:25.300 --> 00:22:28.350
the permission to go ahead and
work very hard on this dream

00:22:28.350 --> 00:22:29.400
of WorldWide Telescope.

00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:33.270
So this is why Jim's
picture is on the slide.

00:22:33.270 --> 00:22:36.680
And Google Sky came out first
because WorldWide Telescope

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:37.470
was very guarded.

00:22:37.470 --> 00:22:38.690
And they didn't want
to release the software

00:22:38.690 --> 00:22:40.000
before it was done.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.340
But anyway, I used to have
to go around and explain

00:22:42.340 --> 00:22:45.190
that WorldWide Telescope was
like Google Sky only better

00:22:45.190 --> 00:22:47.480
and that even though
I'm a big Apple Machead,

00:22:47.480 --> 00:22:49.200
I was working with
Microsoft because it

00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:50.272
was this amazing stuff.

00:22:50.272 --> 00:22:52.230
But I don't really have
to explain that anymore

00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:53.930
because now it's an
open source project.

00:22:53.930 --> 00:22:54.430
OK.

00:22:54.430 --> 00:23:00.230
So then, the government effort
was not managed optimally.

00:23:00.230 --> 00:23:05.960
And the project was
canceled in 2014

00:23:05.960 --> 00:23:07.920
even though, actually,
much more money had

00:23:07.920 --> 00:23:09.990
been awarded in the interim.

00:23:09.990 --> 00:23:12.540
And that's why the
logo had changed.

00:23:12.540 --> 00:23:15.520
But what's important is
that also in 2014 and then

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:17.780
ultimately 2015,
Microsoft Research

00:23:17.780 --> 00:23:19.530
agreed to open source
WorldWide Telescope.

00:23:19.530 --> 00:23:21.750
So that's why we have
the little GitHub thing.

00:23:21.750 --> 00:23:25.020
So the two things that are going
are the standards, the IVOA,

00:23:25.020 --> 00:23:29.220
and the software project
WorldWide Telescope.

00:23:29.220 --> 00:23:33.060
So just for reference, this is
what Google Sky looks like now.

