finding where in the sky it is.

00:57:01.840 --> 00:57:02.700
How do you do that?

00:57:02.700 --> 00:57:03.320
ALYSSA GOODMAN: Oh, yes.

00:57:03.320 --> 00:57:03.820
OK.

00:57:03.820 --> 00:57:05.966
So that's this
astrometry.net program.

00:57:05.966 --> 00:57:08.340
And there used to be these
sort of brute force algorithms

00:57:08.340 --> 00:57:10.381
that would actually just
look for things at known

00:57:10.381 --> 00:57:11.780
positional orientations.

00:57:11.780 --> 00:57:16.990
But the way this actually works
now is groups of four stars

00:57:16.990 --> 00:57:18.720
that they call quads
are identified.

00:57:18.720 --> 00:57:20.590
And then, they look
for the-- if you

00:57:20.590 --> 00:57:23.390
draw an X or a twisted
X between those,

00:57:23.390 --> 00:57:25.680
then the length of those
lines and the angle

00:57:25.680 --> 00:57:28.430
between those lines is a
very unique fingerprint

00:57:28.430 --> 00:57:30.470
if you have a bunch of
those quads in an image.

00:57:30.470 --> 00:57:33.320
And so it's compared against
a catalogue of the sky.

00:57:33.320 --> 00:57:35.220
And it's remarkably fast.

00:57:35.220 --> 00:57:37.299
By the way, it's
being used also--

00:57:37.299 --> 00:57:38.840
this thing called
DASCH, which stands

00:57:38.840 --> 00:57:41.860
for Digital Access to a
Sky Century at Harvard.

00:57:41.860 --> 00:57:46.390
So we own 600,000 glass
plate images of the sky.

00:57:46.390 --> 00:57:48.840
It's the largest
collection of images.

00:57:48.840 --> 00:57:51.070
It goes back 100 years.

00:57:51.070 --> 00:57:52.680
And so that
astrometry.net program

00:57:52.680 --> 00:57:56.550
is actually also be used to
solve for the coordinates

00:57:56.550 --> 00:57:58.090
of these historical plates.

00:57:58.090 --> 00:58:00.090
And hopefully, we'll wind
up with all those data

00:58:00.090 --> 00:58:02.240
in WorldWide Telescope as well.

00:58:02.240 --> 00:58:04.820
And by the way, you can't
get 100 years of time series

00:58:04.820 --> 00:58:06.660
without waiting 100 years.

00:58:06.660 --> 00:58:11.360
So even in the data that are
kind of crappy and very old

00:58:11.360 --> 00:58:12.660
are incredibly valuable.

00:58:12.660 --> 00:58:16.280
Because even if you have LLST,
to get 100 year time baseline,

00:58:16.280 --> 00:58:17.882
you have to wait 100 years.

